               <p>7. 
               
                  <persName id="t17751206-5-defend378" type="defendantName">
                     CHARLES
                      CHAPMAN
                  <interp inst="t17751206-5-defend378" type="surname" value="CHAPMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-defend378" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-defend378" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            , indicted for <rs id="t17751206-5-off17" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-off17" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-off17" type="offenceSubcategory" value="housebreaking"></interp>
               breaking into the dwelling-house of 
                     <persName id="t17751206-5-person379">
                        Benjamin
                         Viles
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person379" type="surname" value="Viles"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t17751206-5-person379" type="given" value="Benjamin"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t17751206-5-person379" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                  , and stealing a bank note for 30 l. &amp;c
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>[By desire of the Prisoner the Witnesses were examined separate.]</p>
               <p>
            
               
                  <persName id="t17751206-5-victim381" type="victimName">
                     BENJAMIN
                      VILES
                  <interp inst="t17751206-5-victim381" type="surname" value="VILES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-victim381" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-victim381" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t17751206-5-off17 t17751206-5-victim381"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            . I am a <rs id="t17751206-5-viclabel18" type="occupation">butcher</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17751206-5-victim381 t17751206-5-viclabel18"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t17751206-5-crimeloc19">Oxford Market</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17751206-5-crimeloc19" type="placeName" value="Oxford Market"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17751206-5-crimeloc19" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17751206-5-off17 t17751206-5-crimeloc19"></join>; I have known 
               <persName id="t17751206-5-person382">
                  Charles
                   Chapman
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person382" type="surname" value="Chapman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person382" type="given" value="Charles"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person382" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the prisoner five or six years; he was <rs id="t17751206-5-deflabel20" type="occupation">apprentice to a butcher</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17751206-5-defend378 t17751206-5-deflabel20"></join> in Oxford Market, but run away. On Saturday night, the <rs id="t17751206-5-cd21" type="crimeDate">2d of December</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17751206-5-off17 t17751206-5-cd21"></join>, my wife called out that they were robbed and ruined; I ran from the shop where I was to the house, about forty yards distance, and found the parlour window broke open; no body was in the house, we were all at the shop. My wife was just going home to make the bed when she discovered it; a pane of glass was broke in the window: he had put in his hand and unscrewed that which secured the shutters; the bureau in the fore parlour was broke, and a note of 30 l. gone, which was in the bureau: I had not been in the house since morning.</p>
               <p>Did you see the note again? - Yes; I have it here.</p>
               <p>Do you know who it is signed by, or the number and date? - No.</p>
               <p>How do you know then that it is yours? - To the best of my knowledge it is the same; I had not seen it for three weeks before. (The Note was produced in Court by Mr. Barker.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17751206-5-person383">
                  BENJAMIN
                   VILES
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person383" type="surname" value="VILES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person383" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person383" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the prosecutor, look at the note; can you swear that that is the note you lost? - No; not positively: I lost between four and five pounds, besides two guineas in gold, six and thirty and six-pence: the prisoner gave it to one 
               <persName id="t17751206-5-person384">
                  Benjamin
                   Lewis
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person384" type="surname" value="Lewis"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person384" type="given" value="Benjamin"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person384" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , who took him about half an hour after the robbery was committed; I heard him acknowledge the robbery: there was likewise a silver studd I have had these twenty years, which I know to be mine by a twist in the bottom, found on the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17751206-5-person385">
                  MARGARET
                   VILES
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person385" type="surname" value="VILES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person385" type="given" value="MARGARET"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person385" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Are you the wife of 
               <persName id="t17751206-5-person386">
                  Benjamin
                   Viles
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person386" type="surname" value="Viles"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person386" type="given" value="Benjamin"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person386" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the prosecutor? - Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177512060036"></xptr>On Saturday night, the 2d of December, I went home, and found the parlour window broke open; I had secured it the Friday evening, saw it again the Saturday morning, and it was then fast. I went into the house many times that day; between twelve and one o'clock I went into the parlour for change, and found it then fast; I did not go again till near eleven, when I went to make my bed, and found the parlour window thrown up, was much surprized, thinking it had been left open: I saw the bureau broke, and all the writings thrown about; I called to my husband, who came. - We missed a 30 l. note, which I had put into the bureau about three weeks before with my own hand; I don't know the note, as it belonged to another person, who was in liquor, and gave it to me to keep for him: there were two guineas in gold and some silver, between four and five pounds in all missing: I saw this money the day before in the bureau, and the keys were in my own pocket; the prisoner acknowledged the whole.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17751206-5-person387">
                  BENJAMIN
                   LEWIS
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person387" type="surname" value="LEWIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person387" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person387" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Hearing of Mr. Viles being robbed, I went to him; he said there were some people whom he suspected: we missed the prisoner from the market; Mrs. Viles desired me to look after him: I went into the sign of the Red Lion, in Oxford-street, and there found him: I desired him to go with me; and coming near the market, he seemed unwilling: I told him he must go to Mr. Viles; he then said it did not signify denying it; he took out a handkerchief, and gave me the note, and three or four pounds in money: I took the note, but desired him to give my uncle the money, I gave the note to Mrs. Viles.</p>
               <p>Did you see him deliver the money to Mrs. Viles? - When he came to the door he took it in his hands and threw it on the ground, and said that he had lost or mislaid it, and said that was all; I saw him throw the money down at Mr. Viles's door.</p>
               <p>[Mrs. Viles was again called, and asked if she saw the prisoner throw the money down at the door? she said she did not see it herself, but that her daughter and 
               <persName id="t17751206-5-person388">
                  Benjamin
                   Lewis
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person388" type="surname" value="Lewis"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person388" type="given" value="Benjamin"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person388" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and the watchman, saw him: Lewis said he was not half a minute about it.]</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17751206-5-person389">
                  JOHN
                   AYRES
               <interp inst="t17751206-5-person389" type="surname" value="AYRES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person389" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-person389" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (son-in-law to the prosecutor) I had a suspicion of the prisoner as I saw him go past my father's shop door after ten o'clock, when we discovered that the house had been broke open: I went with Mr. Lewis in search of the prisoner, and found him at the Red Lion, in Oxford-street: I stood at the door; Mr. Lewis went in and brought him out; when coming down Oxford-street, he said it did not signify denying it, he was the person.</p>
               <p>Was you at Mr. Lewis's door when the prisoner threw down the money? - Yes; he threw it down with violence, and said that was the money: my father's man picked up two guineas in gold, and six and thirty and sixpence in silver, which the prisoner threw down.</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>Please you, my Lord, I am guilty of the fact; but it is my first offence. When Lewis took me at the Red Lion, I might have destroyed the note; but he told me, if I would deliver up his uncle's property he would not hurt me.</p>
               <p>Mr. Lewis was asked if he said so? - He said he told the prisoner, if he would deliver up the property, Mr. Viles would be as easy as the law would admit of.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17751206-5-verdict22" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-verdict22" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. <rs id="t17751206-5-punish23" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17751206-5-punish23" type="punishmentCategory" value="death"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t17751206-5-defend378 t17751206-5-punish23"></join>
               Death
            </rs>.</p>
